@* Counter — the Filament generator's INPUT. Phase 2.

   THE TEMPLATE BELOW IS baseline/Counter.Blazor/App.razor's MARKUP, VERBATIM,
   BLANK LINES INCLUDED. It is the SHARED DOM CONTRACT and must not be altered --
   including the blank lines between the siblings, which Blazor's own compiler turns
   into real "\n\n" text nodes (verified from its generated BuildRenderTree, which
   emits AddMarkupContent(0, "<h1 id=\"title\">Counter</h1>\n\n")). They are part of
   the contract precisely BECAUSE they are easy to drop without noticing.

   THE @code BLOCK IS HAND-WRITTEN JAVASCRIPT, not C#. Phase 2 compiles the template
   only -- "la logique @code reste ecrite en JS a la main" (spec 6).

   WHY JS SURVIVES IN @code, VERIFIED AND NOT ASSUMED.
   Razor lexes @code as C# but does not parse or type-check it: the whole block
   arrives in the IR as ONE opaque CSharpCodeIntermediateNode token holding the body
   verbatim, with ZERO Razor diagnostics. `--dump-ir` shows it, and
   GeneratorTests.CodeBlock_IsOpaque_AndCarriesJsVerbatim pins it, byte for byte,
   so that a Razor version that starts parsing this block FAILS A TEST instead of
   silently mangling the app's state. The generator splices this text, untouched,
   into the top of mount().

   State is declared as a signal here because that lifting is Phase 3's job (a C#
   `private int currentCount` would be lifted to Signal<int> by the compiler); with a
   JS seam, the author does it by hand. That is what makes the template's
   @currentCount compile to `currentCount.value` -- a read of a signal, per decision
   22's property-access protocol -- and not to a bare `currentCount`, which would
   setText an object and print "[object Object]". *@

<h1 id="title">Counter</h1>

<p>Current count: <span id="counter-value">@currentCount</span></p>

<button id="increment" @onclick="Increment">Click me</button>

@code {
    const currentCount = signal(0);

    const Increment = () => {
        currentCount.value++;
    };
}
